<section class="section-divider" id="finding">
  <div class="prose-section">
    <div class="num-label"><span class="num">01</span> The discovery</div>
    <h2>Your chatbot keeps a journal</h2>

    <p>
      When a language model answers you, billions of numbers churn in silence. Ask the model what
      any one of them means and it can't tell you — most of its own machinery is as opaque to it
      as your neurons are to you. But in early 2026, interpretability researchers found an
      exception: a thin <strong>band of late layers</strong> where something remarkable happens.
      Whatever is written there, the model can <em>read back out in words</em>.
    </p>

    <p>
      Nudge the model inside this band, and it will later tell you — in plain English — what
      changed. Nudge it anywhere else, and it can't. The band behaves like a
      <strong>journal</strong>: the one place in the machine where its internal states are legible,
      to itself and to us. And the same researchers shipped a reading instrument for it — a
      mathematical lens that translates the journal's contents into ordinary vocabulary.
    </p>

    <div class="callout">
      <div class="callout-title">Why care?</div>
      <p>
        Everything we want from AI oversight — auditing, debugging, safety — starts with
        legibility. A journal you can read is rare enough. This one, it turns out, you can also
        <em>write in</em>. That's where the story starts, and where it nearly went wrong.
      </p>
    </div>

    <details class="expand">
      <summary>For researchers: the J-space, precisely</summary>
      <div class="expand-body">
        <p>
          The workspace is defined <em>functionally</em>: a representation is in it if an
          intervened model can subsequently report the intervention in text. The instrument is the
          <strong>Jacobian lens</strong> — the average input–output Jacobian
          <code>J<sub>ℓ</sub> = E[∂h<sub>final</sub>/∂h<sub>ℓ</sub>]</code> used as a linear transport, decoded with the
          model's own unembedding: <code>lens<sub>ℓ</sub>(h) = W<sub>U</sub> J<sub>ℓ</sub> h</code>. The verbalizable band
          ("J-space") sits at layers 24–31 on the 32-layer models studied here; band structure is
          measured by CKA band contrast (0.14–0.31 across the three plants in loops L1/L1b/L2).
        </p>
      </div>
    </details>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section-divider" id="gap" style="padding-top:0;">
  <div class="prose-section">
    <div class="num-label"><span class="num">02</span> The problem</div>
    <h2>Nobody knew the rules of writing</h2>

    <p>
      Here's the situation the field found itself in. Imagine being handed a pen that writes
      directly into someone's stream of thought — and no instructions. Write <em>what</em>,
      exactly? Write <em>where</em> on the page? <em>When</em> — mid-sentence, or while the writer
      pauses? How do you check the thought actually <em>landed</em>, rather than just smudging the
      page? And the question nobody wanted to ask: what does each written word <em>cost</em> the
      mind you're writing into?
    </p>

    <p>
      These aren't rhetorical worries. Later in this essay you'll watch what happens when you
      write carelessly: the model does what you ask — and pays for it with
      <strong>four times</strong> its safe budget of "freedom," drifting toward a single fixation.
      Steering a mind, it turns out, needs a control theory. In 2026, none existed.
    </p>

    <p>
      The surprise of this project — and the reason this essay exists — is <em>where</em> a
      complete, testable control theory was already waiting. Not in a robotics textbook.
      In 10th-century Kashmir.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>
